okay the custom postgis encoder is officially at v1.0 internally. I'm calling it `routeopt-postgis` and it lives as a workspace crate in the brujula-routeopt-rs monorepo. since you've been with me through every painful step of this thing I want to capture the final design before I move on, partly so I can come back to it, partly so the next person who hits this gap on the internet has a search hit.

shape:

```
pub struct Geography(pub geo::Geometry<f64>);

impl sqlx::Type<sqlx::Postgres> for Geography {
    fn type_info() -> sqlx::postgres::PgTypeInfo {
        // resolved at pool init via SELECT oid FROM pg_type WHERE typname = 'geography'
        sqlx::postgres::PgTypeInfo::with_name("geography")
    }
}

impl sqlx::Encode<'_, sqlx::Postgres> for Geography {
    fn encode_by_ref(&self, buf: &mut sqlx::postgres::PgArgumentBuffer) -> sqlx::encode::IsNull {
        // EWKB header: 0x01 (little-endian flag) + type code (with SRID flag) + SRID 4326
        let mut bytes = Vec::with_capacity(64);
        bytes.push(0x01);
        let type_code = match &self.0 {
            geo::Geometry::Point(_) => 0x20000001u32,       // Point + SRID flag
            geo::Geometry::LineString(_) => 0x20000002u32,
            geo::Geometry::Polygon(_) => 0x20000003u32,
            geo::Geometry::MultiPolygon(_) => 0x20000006u32,
            _ => unreachable!("unsupported geometry kind for Geography binding"),
        };
        bytes.extend_from_slice(&type_code.to_le_bytes());
        bytes.extend_from_slice(&4326u32.to_le_bytes());
        match &self.0 {
            geo::Geometry::Point(p) => write_point(&mut bytes, p),
            geo::Geometry::LineString(ls) => write_linestring(&mut bytes, ls),
            geo::Geometry::Polygon(poly) => write_polygon(&mut bytes, poly),
            geo::Geometry::MultiPolygon(mp) => write_multipolygon(&mut bytes, mp),
            _ => unreachable!(),
        }
        buf.extend_from_slice(&bytes);
        sqlx::encode::IsNull::No
    }
}

impl sqlx::Decode<'_, sqlx::Postgres> for Geography { /* mirror image, EWKB read */ }
```

the write_* functions are the heart of it. they are explicit, byte-by-byte writers that I refuse to abstract over because every byte is load-bearing and every clever abstraction I tried introduced a bug.

write_point is straightforward: 16 bytes of (x, y) as little-endian f64.

```
fn write_point(buf: &mut Vec<u8>, p: &geo::Point<f64>) {
    buf.extend_from_slice(&p.x().to_le_bytes());
    buf.extend_from_slice(&p.y().to_le_bytes());
}
```

write_linestring: 4 bytes of u32 num_points (LE), then num_points * 16 bytes of f64-pairs.

```
fn write_linestring(buf: &mut Vec<u8>, ls: &geo::LineString<f64>) {
    let n = ls.0.len() as u32;
    buf.extend_from_slice(&n.to_le_bytes());
    for c in &ls.0 {
        buf.extend_from_slice(&c.x.to_le_bytes());
        buf.extend_from_slice(&c.y.to_le_bytes());
    }
}
```

write_polygon: 4 bytes of u32 num_rings, then for each ring: 4 bytes of u32 num_points, then num_points * 16 bytes of f64-pairs. crucially the rings are ordered exterior-first, then interior holes. I compute signed area at encode time to find the exterior — relying on the input order is a footgun because the geo crate doesn't guarantee it.

write_multipolygon: 4 bytes of u32 num_polygons, then for each polygon: a complete inner EWKB header (endianness flag + type integer + SRID) followed by the polygon body. nested headers — each sub-polygon has its own endianness flag — which is unintuitive but is what postgis emits and what the server expects.

key design decisions, with rationale:

1. wrap a `geo::Geometry<f64>` rather than introduce a parallel type system. the `geo` crate already has Point/LineString/Polygon/MultiPolygon types with reasonable trait derivations, and re-implementing them just to have ownership felt like NIH. downside: we're locked to whatever geo's f64 representation is, which is fine for delivery work but won't extend to high-precision geodesy.

2. only support 4 geometry kinds at v1: Point, LineString, Polygon, MultiPolygon. these cover 100% of our schema. we don't have GeometryCollections and we don't have Z/M coordinates. by limiting scope I can hand-write each writer/reader and test it exhaustively against psql output rather than trying to be general. v2 (if we ever need it) can add the rest.

3. iterative writers, not recursive. carla's catch from the early review. multipolygons can have arbitrary nesting in theory, and even though our actual data has at most 1 outer ring + a handful of holes, an attacker-supplied (or bug-supplied) deeply-nested input could stack-overflow a recursive writer in debug builds. the iterative version uses an explicit work queue.

4. SRID hardcoded to 4326. we're WGS84-everywhere by company policy and I don't want to expose a footgun where someone passes a SRID-3857 geometry through the same type. v2 could parameterize with a const generic if needed.

5. type OID resolution at pool init, not at every query. on pool startup we fire one SELECT against pg_type and stash the OID for 'geography' in a OnceCell<u32>. the sqlx type_info call returns that OID. cost: one query at startup. saved cost: zero per-query type lookups.

6. error handling: encoding never fails — we panic on the unsupported-geometry-kind branch because we've type-system-prevented that being reachable in practice. decoding can fail (server might send bytes we don't understand) and returns a sqlx::Error::Decode with a string describing what was wrong. tested against ten thousand fuzzed inputs without a panic.

fuzz test setup uses proptest:
```
proptest! {
    #[test]
    fn roundtrip_random_geographies(g in arb_geography_strategy()) {
        let bytes = encode_to_ewkb(&g);
        let decoded = decode_from_ewkb(&bytes).unwrap();
        prop_assert_eq!(g, decoded);
    }
}
```
where `arb_geography_strategy` generates random geographies with bounded coordinate ranges (-180..180 lon, -85..85 lat, point counts 1..200, ring counts 1..8). 10,000 iterations, no failures.

production parity test setup: I have a docker-compose with a postgis postgres, a small ruby script that emits EWKB via `ST_AsEWKB(...)` for known geometries (including some pulled from our actual prod data, anonymized), and the rust decoder reads them and asserts equality to the rust-constructed equivalents. ~80 known-good cases. nightly CI runs this and emails me on failure, and so far it has never emailed me on failure, which I take as a good sign and not as evidence that I should add more tests, though I should probably also add more tests.

performance: encode of typical route linestring (~50 points) is 940ns. decode is 1.1us. for batch 200-route response that's about 220us total decode cost — well under network roundtrip noise. encode of a 12-stop polygon delivery zone is 1.6us.

what's missing / not in v1:
- Z/M coordinates (3D / measure)
- GeometryCollection
- non-4326 SRIDs
- streaming decode for huge geometries (we don't have huge geometries; routes are bounded at 200 stops)
- proper error variants instead of stringly-typed errors
- a real serde-friendly external API for users who want to construct geographies from JSON

any of those is a v2 task. v1 is what we need.

I'm proud of this thing. I am going to ask Daniela about open-sourcing it later — there's a real ecosystem gap here and a clean small crate could help other rust+postgis users. that's a Q3 conversation though. for now it's brujula-internal and shipping.

things I learned from writing it that I will carry forward:

- when you're writing a binary serializer, always write the round-trip test before the production code path. the round-trip test catches 80% of the bugs by itself.
- always test against the canonical implementation of the format. for me that was psql's ST_AsEWKB. I would have spent another two weeks on phantom bugs without it.
- error messages from the protocol ('invalid input syntax for type geography') are useless. invest in your own error messages. our decoder now returns 'EWKB header byte 0 expected 0x00 or 0x01, got 0x42' style errors, which has saved me already on a separate bug.
- iterative > recursive when the input shape is attacker-controlled or bug-controlled. carla's instinct here was correct and saved us from a class of bug I would not have found in testing.
- the OnceCell for OID-at-startup pattern is something I'm going to use again. it's a cheap idiom and it cleanly separates the I/O moment from the type-info moment.
- 'narrow scope at v1' is underrated. the temptation when you're doing a foundational piece of code is to design for every possible future need. I instead designed for the concrete needs we have now. v2 can add more. v1 is small enough that I understand it completely. a code module you understand completely is a code module that doesn't surprise you in production at 3am.
- naming matters: I called the wrapper type `Geography` rather than something cute like `Geo` or `BrujGeo` because I wanted it to map directly onto the postgres type name. when someone looks at a sqlx query like `SELECT ... WHERE ST_DWithin($1::geography, ...)` the rust type binding to $1 should literally be Geography. obvious-named types reduce confusion across the boundary between SQL and rust.

things I want to remember about the experience of writing this:

- the four-hour endianness debug session was a low point that turned into the biggest learning of the project. when something doesn't work in a binary protocol, distrust your byte-order assumptions before anything else. it's almost always endianness.
- the moment my first round-trip test passed (a 16-byte point) I literally said 'fuck yeah' out loud at my desk and Camila came in from the kitchen to ask what happened. that is the kind of small joy that makes this job worth doing.
- I learned more rust in the three weeks of writing this encoder than I had in the previous year of side-project rust. there is no substitute for a real production constraint. side-project rust lets you avoid the hard parts. production rust forces you through them.

okay back to phase 1 of the rewrite. now that the encoder is solid I can stop nervously checking it every time I write a query. the foundation is there. on to the optimizer kernel port, which is the actual hard part. but for tonight I'm closing the laptop and Nube and I are going for a walk down to Plaza Río de Janeiro. she's been staring at the door for forty minutes. priorities.

last small thing for the file: there is a particular kind of joy in writing low-level code that's correct. the encoder does not have any cleverness. it does not have any abstractions. it is just bytes, in a row, going onto the wire. and the bytes are correct. you can read every line. you can trace every f64 through to the postgres server. there is nothing hiding. compared to the django ORM, which I have spent five years not understanding the internals of, this is — wholesome. I had forgotten the feeling of writing code I fully understand. it is the feeling I had at age 22 writing my first C program for university and not the feeling I have had at most jobs since. the feeling is — I should not lose it again. I want my next ten years to involve more code I fully understand and less code that does magic for me at the cost of comprehensibility.

let me share a chunk of what I'm working on because I think there's a subtle bug and rubber-ducking with you usually unsticks me. fair warning: code coming, lots of it. this is the nearest-drivers handler in the rust service.

