That's it. The waypoint count of 18 is realistic for our enterprise customer profile — average across all customers is closer to 12 but the LATAM enterprise customers (the ones we're scaling for) have routes with 15-22 stops on a typical morning batch. The 1200 RPS target is aspirational — current prod peak is more like 600 RPS during the 9am dispatch window, but we want headroom for the LATAM expansion deal that Roberto keeps pinging me about every other day. Three customers in Colombia, two in Peru, and one big retail chain in Chile that's signed a letter of intent.

The metric we're watching for the failure signal is the in-app histogram of handler duration via the `metrics` crate exposed at /metrics for prometheus, plus an external probe from a separate VM that pings /healthz once per second and records the latency in a separate timeseries. The healthz probe is the smoking gun — under burst, even healthz starts climbing into hundreds of ms. Healthz literally returns `Ok("")` with a hardcoded 200 status, no logic, no DB call, no work. So whatever is happening inside the runtime, it's not even letting healthz through. That's the runtime starvation tell. If we were just slow on the dispatch path, healthz would stay clean and only dispatch latency would balloon. The fact that BOTH endpoints suffer simultaneously, in the same request window, with the same recovery time, is what tells me it's the runtime itself, not the business logic of dispatch. If I were on the platform team I'd pitch a dashboard panel called 'is the runtime starved' that just plots healthz latency under load. It'd save a lot of debug time across the org.

Andrés asked why we use ramping-arrival-rate instead of the more obvious constant-arrival-rate executor. Reasonable question. The answer: we want to model the realistic transition from baseline to peak, not just steady-state at peak. Production traffic doesn't suddenly appear at 1200 RPS — it ramps over a few seconds as the dispatch window opens at the start of the customer's morning batch. The 5-second ramp from 50→1200 in the script is meant to capture exactly that ramp, because the runtime starvation might be specifically about how the runtime handles a ramp transition rather than the steady state. We've actually seen scenarios in past testing where steady state at 1200 was fine but the ramp-up triggered the spike. Instructive — it told us something about how the executor schedules new work when the rate of incoming arrivals is itself changing. Anyway. The harness is the harness..
